This change adds:
1. A utility function to generate the schema based on the config
2. A CLI command to write the generated schema to disk
3. A new Deno task to run the schema generation
4. A basic CLI entrypoint to handle the command

Now you can run `deno task generate-schema` to automatically generate the adapter.schema.json file based on the theme keys in your config.

You'll need to modify the config.ts slightly to make sure all theme keys are represented consistently between the config and the current schema.

```json core/deno.json
{
  "$schema": "https://deno.land/x/deno/cli/schemas/config-file.v1.json",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "tasks": {
    "install": "deno install --global --allow-read --allow-write --import-map=import_map.json -f -n black-atom-core src/cli.ts",
    "compile": "deno compile --allow-read --allow-write --allow-env --import-map=import_map.json -o black-atom-core src/cli.ts",
    "lock": "deno cache --lock=deno.lock --reload --import-map=import_map.json .",
    "check": "deno check --import-map=import_map.json .",
    "format": "deno fmt .",
    "lint": "deno lint --ignore=deno.lock,deno.json,import_map.json .",
    "schema": "deno run --allow-read --allow-write src/lib/generate-schema.ts"
  },
  "fmt": {
    "useTabs": false,
    "lineWidth": 100,
    "indentWidth": 4,
    "semiColons": true,
    "singleQuote": false,
    "proseWrap": "preserve"
  },
  "importMap": "./import_map.json"
}
```


